      "writtenOn": "2017-12-07T21:53:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I don\u0027t think this is necessary, split(\u0027x\u0027)[0], split(\u0027x/\u0027)[0], and split(\u0027x/y\u0027)[0] all seem to do what you\u0027d need here?\n\u003e \n\u003e Or is it necesssary for the actual \"push\" loop below? In that case, it could move down there.\n\n\u003e\u003e\u003e import posixpath\n\u003e\u003e\u003e posixpath.split(\u0027a/b\u0027)\n(\u0027a\u0027, \u0027b\u0027)\n\u003e\u003e\u003e posixpath.split(\u0027a/b/\u0027)\n(\u0027a/b\u0027, \u0027\u0027)\n\nThat’s no good. I need to treat [0] as the thing to create in both cases.\n\nIt seems like it’d be OK in the second case to mkdir a/b, but there’s a problem if you do that: if a/b exists, then when you “adb push b a/b”, you’ll wind up with it heading into a/b/b. On the other hand, if a exists but a/b doesn’t, it’ll go into a/b, where it belongs.\n\nI’ve addressed this by expanding the comment.",
      "parentUuid": "44a5a880_2acc55b1",
